		<tr valign=top>
			<td class="BoardRowB" colspan=2 width="83%">
				I think the main problem with &quot;nerfed&quot; classes is that the players have overspecialized their characters -- so when a change is made in the rules, characters built specifically to take advantage of that loophole or exploit go the way of the sabertooth tigers.  Think about how we fight monsters -- the casters die first.  The AI is merely using our own tactics against us.  I have been in groups where all a cleric did was heal and med and all the casters did was nuke and med.  In fact, the casters were completely helpless when monsters turned on them -- have sacrificed every possible personal protection for int/wis gear and having neglected their combat skills almost as soon as their characters were created.  Compare these group dependent characters with soloist -- a soloist is forced to make a versatile character.  He cannot walk around with two Steins of Mogguk in his hands -- he needs a weapon (and, if he's a cleric, a sheild is nice).  The heal-aggro rules don't apply to me -- for soloists these rules are irrelevant.  Minor twinking of the rules by Verant to eliminate absurd tactics (like medding in battle) will not destroy a well-balanced character. <br>  <br> Adapt or die.		

			</td>
